                                    title: "The Four Building Blocks of Medical Terms",
                                    content: "Every medical term is constructed from up to four building blocks. Think of them like LEGO pieces - once you know the pieces, you can build (and decode) anything:\n\n**1. WORD ROOT** - The foundation, the core meaning\nThis is the main subject of the term, usually identifying a body part or organ. Example: CARDI = heart, GASTR = stomach, DERM = skin\n\n**2. COMBINING VOWEL** - The glue (usually 'O')\nThis vowel (almost always 'o', sometimes 'i') connects word parts to make pronunciation easier. Example: CARDI + O = CARDIO\n\n**3. PREFIX** - The beginning modifier\nAttached to the FRONT of a word to change its meaning. Example: BRADY- = slow, TACHY- = fast, so BRADYcardia = slow heart, TACHYcardia = fast heart\n\n**4. SUFFIX** - The ending that tells the story\nAttached to the END - often tells you what's being DONE or what KIND of term this is. Example: -ITIS = inflammation, -ECTOMY = surgical removal, -OLOGY = study of\n\nNot every medical term has all four parts, but EVERY term has at least a word root and usually a suffix.",
