                                    content: "The word root is the CORE of every medical term - it's the foundation that everything else is built upon. Most word roots refer to body parts, organs, or tissues.\n\n**ESSENTIAL WORD ROOTS TO KNOW:**\n\n**Head & Senses:**\nCEPHAL = head | ENCEPHAL = brain | OT = ear | OPHTHALM = eye | RHIN = nose | OR = mouth | GLOSS/LINGU = tongue\n\n**Chest & Heart:**\nCARDI = heart | PULMON/PNEUM = lung | THORAC = chest | ANGI = vessel\n\n**Abdomen:**\nGASTR = stomach | HEPAT = liver | ENTER = intestine | COL = colon | CYST = bladder/sac | NEPHR/REN = kidney\n\n**Structure:**\nOSTE = bone | ARTHR = joint | MY/MYOS = muscle | DERM = skin | NEUR = nerve | HEM/HEMAT = blood\n\n**KEY INSIGHT:** Most word roots come from either Greek or Latin. Sometimes BOTH languages have a word for the same body part:\n- Kidney: NEPHR (Greek) and REN (Latin) - both are used!\n- Nose: RHIN (Greek) and NAS (Latin) - both are used!\n\nThis is why you might see 'nephritis' AND 'renal failure' - same organ, different language origins!",
