                                    content: "Medical terms can look intimidating, but pronunciation follows patterns. Here are the key rules:\n\n**COMMON ENDINGS & HOW TO SAY THEM:**\n\n-ITIS (eye-tis): inflammation ‚Üí gastRITIS, arthRITIS\n-ECTOMY (ek-toh-mee): surgical removal ‚Üí appendECTOMY\n-OLOGY (ol-oh-jee): study of ‚Üí cardiOLOGY\n-OSCOPY (os-koh-pee): viewing with scope ‚Üí colonOSCOPY\n-PLASTY (plas-tee): surgical repair ‚Üí rhinoPLASTY\n-MEGALY (meg-ah-lee): enlargement ‚Üí hepatoMEGALY\n\n**ACCENT RULES:**\nUsually stress the syllable BEFORE the suffix:\n- car-dee-OL-oh-jee (cardiology)\n- gas-TRY-tis (gastritis)\n- hep-ah-toh-MEG-ah-lee (hepatomegaly)\n\n**SILENT LETTERS:**\n- PS at the beginning = just 'S' sound: PSYchology = sye-KOL-oh-jee\n- PN at the beginning = just 'N' sound: PNEUmonia = new-MOH-nee-ah\n- PT at the beginning = just 'T' sound: PTosis = TOH-sis\n\n**PRO TIP:** When in doubt, break the word into its parts and pronounce each part separately, then blend them together!",
