                                    title: "The Anatomical Position: Starting Point",
                                    content: "Before we can describe WHERE something is in the body, we need a standard reference point. That's the ANATOMICAL POSITION - and it's ALWAYS the starting point.\n\n**THE ANATOMICAL POSITION:**\n- Standing UPRIGHT (erect)\n- Facing FORWARD\n- Arms at the SIDES\n- Palms facing FORWARD (thumbs pointing OUT)\n- Feet parallel, toes pointing forward\n\n**WHY PALMS FORWARD?**\nThis is the key detail people forget! With palms forward:\n- The RADIUS and ULNA bones are parallel (not crossed)\n- The thumb is on the LATERAL (outer) side\n- Anatomical terms remain consistent regardless of actual patient position\n\n**CRITICAL CONCEPT:**\nEven if a patient is lying down, upside down, or in any other position, we ALWAYS describe their anatomy as if they were in anatomical position. This prevents confusion and ensures everyone speaks the same language.\n\n**Example:** 'The wound is on the anterior surface of the arm' means the FRONT of the arm - even if the patient is lying face down!",
